- **JavaScript Logic:** Contains the BinaryTree and TreeNode classes to manage the tree's structure, handle node insertion, and render the tree interactively.
- **Interaction:** Users can click to add nodes and highlight paths to enhance their understanding of binary trees visually.

This design provides an engaging way for users to learn and interact with a binary tree through direct manipulation and visual feedback.

Certainly! Below is a detailed design for an interactive HTML page that teaches the concept of a Stack, along with the relevant code implementation.

### Interactive Design Plan

#### Concept Title:
**Understanding the Stack Data Structure**

#### Learning Objective:
By the end of this module, users should understand the basic principles of the Stack data structure, including the operations of push, pop, and peek, along with the Last In, First Out (LIFO) characteristic.

#### Interaction Design:
1. **Pushing to the Stack:** Users can type a value into an input field and click the "Push" button. The value will animate and visually appear on top of the stack illustration.

2. **Popping from the Stack:** When users click the "Pop" button, the top value will animate off the stack and fade away, demonstrating the LIFO principle.

3. **Peeking into the Stack:** Users can click the "Peek" button to reveal the top element without removing it, displaying a message above the stack.

4. **Visual Feedback:** Each button click will trigger animations:
   - **Push:** New elements will slide in from the top.
   - **Pop:** The top element will slide out and fade.
   - **Peek:** The top value will visually highlight (e.g., change color) for a brief moment.

#### Layout Description:
- The page will have a simple vertical layout:
    - A header with the title centered at the top.
    - A section for user inputs (input field and buttons) aligned centrally.
    - A visual representation of the stack below the input section.
    - Messages showing the results of action (such as the peeked value) displayed just above the stack.
- The content will have a **24 px margin** on the sides and **16 px spacing** between buttons and the stack to keep the layout clean.
- The design will be responsive, ensuring usability on various screen sizes.

### Implementation
Here is the self-contained implementation using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Stack Module</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 24px;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }

        h1 {
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }

        .controls {
            display: flex;
            gap: 16px;
            margin-bottom: 24px;
        }

        input {
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            border: none;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: #fff;
            border-radius: 4px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }

        #stack {
            width: 100px;
            height: 200px;
            border: 2px dashed #007BFF;
            position: relative;
            overflow: hidden;
            background-color: white;
        }

        .item {
            position: absolute;
            width: 100px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 4px;
            box-shadow: 0px 0px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
            transition: transform 0.5s ease, opacity 0.5s ease;
        }

        #message {
            margin-top: 12px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        @media (max-width: 640px) {
            #stack {
                width: 80%;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
    <h1>Understanding the Stack Data Structure</h1>
    <div class="controls">
        <input type="text" id="stackInput" placeholder="Enter a value" />
        <button id="pushButton">Push</button>
        <button id="popButton">Pop</button>
        <button id="peekButton">Peek</button>
    </div>
    <div id="stack"></div>
    <div id="message"></div>

    <script>
        const stack = [];
        const stackContainer = document.getElementById('stack');
        const input = document.getElementById('stackInput');
        const message = document.getElementById('message');

        const updateStackVisual = () => {
            stackContainer.innerHTML = '';
            stack.forEach((item, index) => {
                const stackItem = document.createElement('div');
                stackItem.className = 'item';
                stackItem.textContent = item;
                stackItem.style.transform = `translateY(${(stack.length - index - 1) * 40}px)`;
                stackContainer.appendChild(stackItem);
            });
        };

        document.getElementById('pushButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
            const value = input.value.trim();
            if (value) {
                stack.push(value);
                updateStackVisual();
                input.value = '';
            }
        });

        document.getElementById('popButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
            if (stack.length > 0) {
                const poppedItem = stack.pop();
                updateStackVisual();
                message.textContent = `Popped: ${poppedItem}`;
            } else {
                message.textContent = 'Stack is empty!';
            }
        });

        document.getElementById('peekButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
            if (stack.length > 0) {
                const topItem = stack[stack.length - 1];
                message.textContent = `Peek: ${topItem}`;
                // Visual feedback for peek
                const peekItem = document.createElement('div');
                peekItem.className = 'item';
                peekItem.textContent = topItem;
                peekItem.style.transform = `translateY(${(stack.length - 1) * 40}px)`;
                peekItem.style.backgroundColor = '#FF4500'; // Highlight color
                stackContainer.appendChild(peekItem);
                setTimeout(() => {
                    stackContainer.removeChild(peekItem);
                }, 1000); // Remove highlight after 1 second
            } else {
                message.textContent = 'Stack is empty!';
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>

</html>
```

### Key Features of the Implementation:
- **Push, Pop, and Peek Operations:** Users can interact with the Stack data structure in a visually understandable manner.
- **Dynamic Visual Updates:** The stack changes with animations based on user input, reinforcing the LIFO concept.
- **Responsive Design:** The layout adjusts to different screen sizes while maintaining usability.
- **Accessibility Considerations:** Buttons and input fields are large enough with clear labels for users of different abilities.

